# Context-Free Grammars (CFG)

## Context-free grammars

### Formal definition

A **context-free grammar** is a quadruple
$$
G = \langle V, \Sigma, P, S \rangle
$$
where:

* $V$ is a finite set of variables (nonterminals),
* $\Sigma$ is a finite alphabet of terminals with $V \cap \Sigma = \varnothing$,
* $S \in V$ is the start symbol,
* $P \subseteq V \times (V \cup \Sigma)^*$ is a finite set of productions.

Productions are written $A \to \alpha$ with $A \in V$ and $\alpha \in (V \cup \Sigma)^*$.

The defining restriction is that the left-hand side consists of exactly one variable; no contextual information is permitted.

---

### Derivation and sentential forms

Define $(V \cup \Sigma)^*$ as the set of **sentential forms**. The one-step derivation relation $\Rightarrow_G \subseteq (V \cup \Sigma)^* \times (V \cup \Sigma)^*$ is defined by
$$
\gamma A \delta \Rightarrow_G \gamma \alpha \delta
$$
whenever $A \to \alpha \in P$ and $\gamma, \delta \in (V \cup \Sigma)^*$.

The reflexiveŌĆōtransitive closure is denoted $\Rightarrow_G^*$.

A string $w \in \Sigma^*$ is **generated** by $G$ iff
$$
S \Rightarrow_G^* w.
$$

The language generated by $G$ is
$$
L(G) = { w \in \Sigma^* \mid S \Rightarrow_G^* w }.
$$

---

### Leftmost and rightmost derivations

A **leftmost derivation** restricts $\Rightarrow_G$ so that the rewritten variable is the leftmost variable in the sentential form. Analogously, a **rightmost derivation** rewrites the rightmost variable.

For every $w \in L(G)$:
$$
S \Rightarrow_G^* w
;;\Longleftrightarrow;;
S \Rightarrow_{\mathrm{lm}}^* w
;;\Longleftrightarrow;;
S \Rightarrow_{\mathrm{rm}}^* w.
$$

Leftmost derivations correspond to top-down parsing; rightmost derivations correspond to bottom-up parsing.

---

### Parse trees

A **parse tree** for $w \in L(G)$ is an ordered rooted tree satisfying:

* Each internal node is labeled by a variable in $V$.
* Each leaf is labeled by a symbol in $V \cup \Sigma \cup {\varepsilon}$.
* For every internal node labeled $A$ with children labeled $\alpha_1 \dots \alpha_k$, there exists a production
  $$
  A \to \alpha_1 \dots \alpha_k \in P.
  $$

The yield of the tree, obtained by reading terminal leaves left-to-right and deleting $\varepsilon$, equals $w$.

Parse trees are invariant under the choice of derivation strategy up to ordering.

---

### Ambiguity

A grammar $G$ is **ambiguous** iff there exists $w \in L(G)$ with two distinct parse trees. A language $L$ is **inherently ambiguous** iff every grammar $G$ with $L(G) = L$ is ambiguous.

Ambiguity is undecidable for CFGs:
$$
\text{AMBIGUOUS} = { \langle G \rangle \mid G \text{ is ambiguous} }
$$
is undecidable.

---

### Grammar formation and normalization

#### Useless symbols

A variable $A \in V$ is **useful** iff:

* $A \Rightarrow_G^* w$ for some $w \in \Sigma^*$,
* $S \Rightarrow_G^* \gamma A \delta$ for some $\gamma, \delta$.

All useless symbols can be eliminated while preserving $L(G)$.

---

#### $\varepsilon$-productions

A production $A \to \varepsilon$ is an $\varepsilon$-production. All $\varepsilon$-productions can be eliminated except possibly $S \to \varepsilon$ if $\varepsilon \in L(G)$.

---

#### Unit productions

A **unit production** has the form $A \to B$ with $A, B \in V$. Unit productions can be eliminated by computing the unit-closure relation
$$
A \Rightarrow_{\mathrm{unit}}^* B
$$
and lifting non-unit productions accordingly.

---

### Normal forms

#### Chomsky normal form

A grammar is in **Chomsky normal form** if all productions are of the form
$$
A \to BC
\quad\text{or}\quad
A \to a
$$
with $A,B,C \in V$ and $a \in \Sigma$, plus optionally $S \to \varepsilon$.

Every context-free language $L \neq {\varepsilon}$ has a CFG in CNF, computable in polynomial time.

CNF enables:

* CYK parsing in $O(n^3)$ time,
* algebraic treatment via derivation matrices.

---

#### Greibach normal form

A grammar is in **Greibach normal form** if all productions have the form
$$
A \to a \alpha
$$
where $a \in \Sigma$ and $\alpha \in V^*$, with $S \to \varepsilon$ allowed if $\varepsilon \in L(G)$.

GNF ensures that every leftmost derivation emits exactly one terminal per step.

---

### Expressive power

CFGs generate exactly the class $\mathrm{CFL}$, characterized equivalently by:

* nondeterministic pushdown automata,
* derivation trees of finite branching,
* algebraic formal power series.

Strict inclusions:
$$
\mathrm{REG} \subsetneq \mathrm{CFL} \subsetneq \mathrm{CSL}.
$$

CFGs cannot express:

* cross-serial dependencies,
* duplication ${ ww \mid w \in \Sigma^* }$,
* equality constraints across multiple unbounded counters.

---

### Closure properties

The class $\mathrm{CFL}$ is closed under:

* union,
* concatenation,
* Kleene star,
* homomorphism,
* inverse homomorphism,
* intersection with regular languages.

$\mathrm{CFL}$ is not closed under:

* intersection,
* complement,
* difference.

---

### Decidability results

Decidable for CFGs:

* emptiness: $L(G) = \varnothing$,
* finiteness,
* membership $w \in L(G)$,
* reachability of variables.

Undecidable:
$$
\text{EQUIV}*{\mathrm{CFG}} = { \langle G_1, G_2 \rangle \mid L(G_1) = L(G_2) }
$$
$$
\text{INCLUSION}*{\mathrm{CFG}} = { \langle G_1, G_2 \rangle \mid L(G_1) \subseteq L(G_2) }
$$

---

### Computational complexity

* Membership via CYK: $O(n^3)$ time, $O(n^2)$ space.
* General parsing lower bound: $\Omega(n^3)$ under standard Boolean matrix multiplication assumptions.
* Deterministic subclasses enable linear-time parsing.

---

### Relations to logic and verification

CFGs correspond to:

* existential second-order logic over trees,
* inductive definitions in fixed-point logics,
* stack-based models in pushdown model checking.

---

### Related topics

* Pushdown automata
* Chomsky normal form
* Greibach normal form
* Parsing algorithms
* Inherent ambiguity
* Context-sensitive grammars
* Algebraic language theory

