## Normal Forms: Chomsky Normal Form

### Formal Definition

A context-free grammar $G = \langle V, \Sigma, P, S \rangle$ is in **Chomsky Normal Form** if every production in $P$ is of one of the following forms:

* $A \to BC$ where $A,B,C \in V$ and $B \ne S$, $C \ne S$
* $A \to a$ where $A \in V$ and $a \in \Sigma$
* Optionally $S \to \epsilon$ if $\epsilon \in L G$ and $S$ does not appear on the right-hand side of any production

All other productions are disallowed.

---

### Structural Properties

* Right-hand sides have length exactly $2$ for nonterminal productions and exactly $1$ for terminal productions.
* No $\epsilon$-productions except possibly $S \to \epsilon$.
* No unit productions $A \to B$.
* No mixed terminalŌĆōnonterminal right-hand sides.
* All derivation trees are binary trees except possibly a single leaf $\epsilon$.

---

### Equivalence Preservation

For every context-free grammar $G$ there exists a grammar $G'$ in Chomsky Normal Form such that:

$$
L G' = L G \setminus { \epsilon }
$$

If $\epsilon \in L G$, then:

$$
L G' = L G
$$

after adding $S \to \epsilon$ with the side condition that $S$ does not occur on any right-hand side.

Language equivalence is preserved modulo $\epsilon$.

---

### Normalization Procedure

Let $G = \langle V, \Sigma, P, S \rangle$ be a context-free grammar.

#### Elimination of Useless Symbols

Remove:

* Non-generating symbols $A$ such that $A \Rightarrow^* w$ for no $w \in \Sigma^*$
* Unreachable symbols not reachable from $S$

This preserves $L G$.

---

#### Elimination of $\epsilon$-Productions

Define the nullable set:

$$
\mathsf{Null} = { A \in V \mid A \Rightarrow^* \epsilon }
$$

For every production:

$$
A \to X_1 X_2 \cdots X_k
$$

add productions obtained by deleting any subset of nullable symbols, excluding the empty right-hand side unless $A = S$.

Remove all $\epsilon$-productions except possibly $S \to \epsilon$.

---

#### Elimination of Unit Productions

Remove productions of the form $A \to B$ where $A,B \in V$.

Define the unit relation:

$$
A \Rightarrow_u B \iff A \Rightarrow^* B \ \text{using only unit productions}
$$

For every $A \Rightarrow_u B$ and every non-unit production $B \to \alpha$, add $A \to \alpha$.

Remove all unit productions.

---

#### Terminal Isolation

For every production with mixed symbols:

$$
A \to X_1 \cdots a \cdots X_k
$$

where $a \in \Sigma$ and $k \ge 2$, introduce a fresh nonterminal $T_a$ and add:

$$
T_a \to a
$$

Replace $a$ with $T_a$ in all such productions.

---

#### Binarization

For any production:

$$
A \to B_1 B_2 \cdots B_k \quad \text{with } k \ge 3
$$

introduce fresh nonterminals $C_1,\ldots,C_{k-2}$ and replace it with:

$$
A \to B_1 C_1
$$

$$
C_1 \to B_2 C_2
$$

$$
\vdots
$$

$$
C_{k-2} \to B_{k-1} B_k
$$

This ensures all productions are binary.

---

### Derivation Tree Properties

For any $w \in L G$ with $|w| = n \ge 1$, every derivation tree in CNF satisfies:

* Exactly $n$ terminal leaves
* Exactly $n-1$ internal nonterminal nodes
* Height bounded by $2n-1$

Every parse tree is a full binary tree modulo terminal leaves.

---

### Complexity Implications

Given a grammar $G$ in CNF and an input string $w$ of length $n$:

* CYK parsing runs in time $O |P| n^3$
* Space complexity $O |V| n^2$

CNF is essential for dynamic programmingŌĆōbased parsing algorithms relying on binary branching.

---

### Pumping Lemma for Context-Free Languages via CNF

If $G$ is in CNF and $|V| = k$, then any derivation tree of height greater than $k$ contains a repeated nonterminal along some root-to-leaf path.

This yields the classical pumping decomposition:

$$
w = uvxyz
$$

with:

* $|vxy| \le 2^k$
* $|vy| \ge 1$
* $\forall i \in \mathbb{N} : uv^i x y^i z \in L$

The exponential bound arises from binary branching.

---

### Decidability and Transformational Properties

* Conversion to CNF is computable in polynomial time.
* CNF preserves ambiguity.
* CNF does not preserve leftmost or rightmost derivation structure.
* CNF simplifies proofs of decidability for membership and emptiness.

---

### Expressive Boundaries

CNF does not increase expressive power:

$$
{ L \mid L \text{ generated by a CNF grammar} } = \text{CFL}
$$

It enforces syntactic regularity without altering language class membership.

---

### Relationship to Logic and Verification

* CNF grammars correspond to binary branching parse trees, aligning with tree automata representations.
* Used in reductions from CFL membership to Boolean matrix multiplication.
* Enables formal verification of syntax via inductive tree invariants.

---

### Related Topics

* Greibach normal form
* CYK algorithm
* Pushdown automata
* Context-free pumping lemma
* Ambiguity in grammars
* Tree automata
* Parsing complexity
* Grammar transformations


